column5: ['Stacey Abrams', 'Tammy Duckworth', 'Kamala Harris', 'Amy Klobuchar', 'Elizabeth Warren', 'Gretchen Whitmer', 'Another woman', 'Someone else not a woman']

column11: In the March Democratic debate, candidate Joe Biden "committed" to picking a woman running mate, while Bernie Sanders said that he would "in all likelihood" do the same (CNN). The outcome will be determined based on the person formally nominated by the Democratic Party as its vice presidential candidate.

Biden is betwern a rock and a hard place in choosing a vp who would keep the more liberal crowd to still go out to vote for him (instead of choosing a third party that is more progressive), while also trying to persuade more of the evangelical sect to vote for Biden instead of Trump. Kamala Harris has the name recognition and the experience to be selected as VP, but she may turn off Middle America, especially the evangelical vote. I think strategically for Biden, he already won the votes of people who claim anybody (you know, any functional adult) is better than Trump. So maybe Harris isn't the best, but she is a woman of color, and that does give her some more value as a vp contender. It is crazy to me to talk of race as something of value to Biden, but we live in a world that minorities (I am a minority) want to be represented in one of the highest offices in the country (and I will be glad when that happens). We also live in a country where Christianity is basically a cornerstone, so those values need to be there, somehow exemplified in a vp candidate. Trump is going to play the card that Biden is not Christian, even though he is Catholic (and many Christians falsely see Catholics as not Christian til this day). Really, hate formulating this forecasr based on demographics but a majority of American votes seem to be persuaded more on race and religious values than merit.

I have spent the last week trying to reconcile my historical analysis of VP picks with the current field of contenders and I just don’t think that my original thesis fits. After some introspection, I feel that my forecast was influenced by response bias. The list of candidates led me to conclude that I had to assign a non-zero probability to each pick, therefore coming up with approaching the question in a way that facilitated such an answer. That’s not to say the research that I did was completely useless as it was a good exercise in contrarian thinking. That being said, there is a growing consensus as we enter the first week of August that the most likely victors in the contest are either Sen. Kamala Harris or former National Security Advisor Susan Rice.

I don’t think there is anyone in Washington or even the entire United States who doesn’t believe this is an unprecedented and unorthodox question to be answering this late in the campaign. The conventional wisdom is that a presidential hopeful chooses his running mate before the general election race begins. Then again, conventional wisdom would also limit one to picking a man as his vice president and that is clearly not the situation we are in now. Despite this being such an unusual point in election history, where a nominee for president has publicly committed himself to choose and a woman and probably an African American one to fill the VP spot, I think many of the standard political considerations still hold true. And those assumptions are what I am going to use to establish my base rates.

Kamala is the most obvious pick from media stories, but she isn't a favorite amongst other California Democrats. Her run for President exposed some organizational flaws that remain hard to overlook. She raised copious amounts of money, but spent it all before the voting began. And in victory, Washington would have both a President and a President-in-Waiting. Harris is definitely young enough to consider another race; her behavior indicates she would put that first over what she owed to Biden. I worry that Harris did not do well in her interview, or that she might not have passed her background check with flying colors. My personal choice would be Bass, but I could also see why Mr. Biden would want Susan Rice (four of their eight years under Obama were spent with each other). He has already mentioned on several occasions how important this personal relationship will be to him. Is Harris someone he can trust? I wouldn't trust her! But I would Bass and Rice.

Karen Bass and Nina Turner, a former Ohio state senator, would make excellent running mates, Sanders delegates to the Democratic National Convention wrote in a letter to Biden that was obtained by The Chronicle." "We have gone through about four candidates so far in the two-hour vetting," Biden said, "and we will get all the vetting done of all the candidates, and then I am going to narrow the list, and then I will have personal discussions with each of the candidates who are left." The most likely option is a woman whom no one has thought of in the zeitgeist. I'm basing that on the fact that there are hundreds, if not over a thousand, female politicians who may meet the criteria for a VP. This is especially poignant when adds to the list prominent republican women, such as Jenean Hampton of Kentucky, who would represent a unity ticket with the explicit goal of beating the incumbent. If Hampton didn't have close ties to the Tea Party, I'd say either her or someone in a similar position were the most likely candidate. Of those who are commonly spoken about, I give Tammy Duckworth the highest odds at 20%. She would check a lot of boxes for a lot constituencies the Biden campaign likely wants to placate. She is from a Midwestern state with a Democratic governor who would appoint a democrat to her seat should she become the VP. She's generally progressive but not to a point where she would become a political liability any more so than Joe Biden himself already is. Stacey Abrams comes in at 16% because she would similarly check a lot of boxes, particularly with the black voters who have propelled Biden to the nomination. The only reason her and Duckworth don't have equal odds is her general lack of experience in elected office. My guess is that the Biden campaign, regardless of who the pick, is assuming that the VP has higher probability of actually becoming president due to Biden's age when entering office. As a result, they are in all likelihood prioritizing government experience over many other factors. Which leads to Gretchen Whitmer at 15%. Whitmer would be a solid pick because of her executive experience however, the fact that she is white and that there was a large amount of dialogue about the primary eventually narrowing down to an effectively all white field works against her potential as a VP pick. On top of that, Michigan has faded from blue to purple over the last election cycles and with the difficult policy decisions related COVID-19 she will have to make, it's likely that Whitmer's favorability will begin to decline in the coming months. Next up we have Biden's former primary opponents. I find it unlikely he will pick a VP from the list of other presidential candidates during the 2020 cycle. Amy Klobochar has better odds than Harris or Warren because she at least did not openly attack Biden in ways that received lots of coverage. She was also not at any point a front runner in the campaign. On top of that, Warren and Harris would both highlight the inconsistent speech patterns of Biden and the last thing the Biden campaign wants is to make their candidate look weak. All that said, i think there is a non-negligible possibility that the Biden campaign picks someone who is not a woman, particularly when one considers that broad range of viable options who are also people of color. I understand Biden made that promise but it would not shock me if they reneged on that promise.

The world is speeding fast. I think there will be considerable pressure on Biden to pick a running mate that is both a woman and a minority group, so I suspect of the known names, Stacey Abrams or Kamala Harris are the only very likely candidates. I think, though, that it is more likely that Joe Biden will pick someone who is not one of the known names. As the world is changing so fast and we're getting new heroes all the time, it's even possible that he might pick a man.

Biden said he's picking a woman, so it's going to be a woman. Stacy Abrams would probably fit in on a Biden team well enough, but against the other women candidates the next biggest box she checks off is the appeal to black voters. Biden does well with that demographic already, owing to 8 years working side-by-side with President Obama, who will be leaving the sidelines to endorse him very soon, so the added value to the ticket maybe isn't there. Likewise, Duckworth is a veteran, and that never hurts, but her home state of Illinois, where she's best known, is not a going concern for the Biden campaign. Warren might be the best prepared to be a useful contributor to a future Biden administration, and if that were to occur she may find herself headed for a cabinet-level position, but she is still just too liberal to be on this ticket, which will inevitably be designed to appeal more broadly across the middle of the ideological spectrum. Of all the former Democratic presidential candidates, Warren was the most feared by Wall street, and the Biden campaign can't afford to lose any Big-money liberal support. Kamala Harris is bringing money to the table herself, with fundraising help and there's lots of money to be raised in her home state of California. But if she's the VP, then she can't be Biden's AG, and with her background as AG of California, that is ultimately probably her best fit in a Biden administration. That leaves Klobuchar and Whitmer. Both bring their popularity in a vital battleground to the table. Minnesota (narrowly won by Clinton in '16) for Klobuchar, and Michigan (narrowly won by Trump in '16) for Whitmer. Klobuchar would be the more traditional pick here, but Whitmer's status has been greatly elevated by her management and actions during the Covid-19 illness crisis occurring in her state and for her willingness to go toe-to-toe with Trump when it came to fighting for her state. Whitmer is still a lesser known quantity on the national stage, but her surging popularity in Michigan could move that state into much more of a sure thing for the Democratic ticket in the fall.
